ications and Nanotechnology and E-MRS 2005, Symposium D, Magnetoelectronics</prism:issuename><dc:creator>Pawlik, P.</dc:creator><dc:creator>Pawlik, K.</dc:creator><dc:creator>Davies, H.A.</dc:creator><dc:creator>Kaszuwara, W.</dc:creator><dc:creator>Wysłocki, J.J.</dc:creator><dc:creator>Harrison, N.</dc:creator><dc:creator>Todd, I.</dc:creator><dc:description>
                  Samples of the Fe60Co13Pr9B14Ti3Zr1 alloy were produced in the form of: (a) ribbons of various thicknesses t by melt-spinning, (b) 1mm diameter rods and (c) thin-walled tubes of outer diameter (o.d.) 3mm, both by suction-casting methods. The microstructure of the thick ribbon samples (with t
                     &gt;100μm) was shown to be a mixture of amorphous and nanocrystalline phases. Furthermore, the rod and tube samples were nanocrystalline in the as-cast state. Relatively high values of coercivity μ
                     0J
                     H
                     c of ∼0.98 and 1.56T were measured, respectively, for the tube and ribbon samples.
