<ce:abstract class="author"><ce:abstract-sec>
<ce:simple-para view="all">Samples of the Fe<ce:inf loc="post">60</ce:inf>Co<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>Pr<ce:inf loc="post">9</ce:inf>B<ce:inf loc="post">14</ce:inf>Ti<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>Zr<ce:inf loc="post">1</ce:inf> alloy were produced in the form of: (a) ribbons of various thicknesses <ce:italic>t</ce:italic> by melt-spinning, (b) 1<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>mm diameter rods and (c) thin-walled tubes of outer diameter (o.d.) 3<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>mm, both by suction-casting methods. The microstructure of the thick ribbon samples (with <ce:italic>t</ce:italic>
<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>&gt;<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>100<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>μm) was shown to be a mixture of amorphous and nanocrystalline phases. Furthermore, the rod and tube samples were nanocrystalline in the as-cast state. Relatively high values of coercivity <ce:italic>μ</ce:italic>
<ce:inf loc="post">0J</ce:inf>
<ce:italic>H</ce:italic>
<ce:inf loc="post">c</ce:inf> of ∼0.98 and 1.56<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>T were measured, respectively, for the tube and ribbon samples.</ce:simple-para>
</ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
